The American Sign Language and Deaf Studies program at George Brown College offers students the opportunity to learn and understand basic ASL conversations, develop English skills, and gain a beginning understanding of the Deaf/ASL community. Students will practice ASL through simulation experiences in the classroom. Career options include using ASL skills in healthcare, business, education, and social services. Fluency in ASL is an asset for interacting with members of the Deaf community or the general public. Graduates may apply to George Brown's Honours Bachelor of Interpretation (American Sign Language – English) program to become American Sign Language-English interpreters. Required courses for Semester 1 include COMM 1022 - English Foundations for ASL Students, SIGN 1056 - Introduction to Anti-Oppressive Practice, SIGN 1057 - ASL Immersion I, SIGN 1058 - ASL Seminar I, and COMM 1000 - Introduction to College Communication.
